rtialFingerprints":{"DATADOG_FINGERPRINT":"7f572b53dfef9c970f631705eec026fe7bc3c58baad8751996f8ec38578d9ca5"},"properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_CATEGORY:BEST_PRACTICES"]},"ruleId":"docker-best-practices/use-absolute-paths","ruleIndex":34}],"tool":{"driver":{"informationUri":"https://www.datadoghq.com","name":"datadog-static-analyzer","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_DIFF_AWARE_CONFIG_DIGEST:9a9e44dc683f6ce6ad78527cd264f1aef9dca93e331ec2b3225106854331871a","DATADOG_EXECUTION_TIME_SECS:0","DATADOG_DIFF_AWARE_ENABLED:false"]},"rules":[{"fullDescription":{"text":"When using a relative `WORKDIR`, you may run into problems since you are dependent on previous `WORKDIR` instructions. Using an absolute `WORKDIR` ensures you have the right path no matter where the instruction is positioned."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/absolute-workdir","id":"docker-best-practices/absolute-workdir","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Use absolute workdir"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"Some commands do not make sense to use when building a container. They require user inputs which cannot work when building a container. Avoid such commands in a Dockerfile."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/avoid-commands-not-relevant","id":"docker-best-practices/avoid-commands-not-relevant","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Avoid commands not made for containers"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"When using `apt-get install`, pin the version to avoid unwanted upgrades and undefined behavior."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/apt-pin-version","id":"docker-best-practices/apt-pin-version","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Always pin versions in apt-get install"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"This rule dictates that Docker images should always be tagged with a specific version number. In Docker, an image tag represents a particular version of an image. The use of tags allows developers to have better control over which versions of an image are being used in their projects. \n\nThis is crucial because it ensures the consistency and reliability of the Docker environment. If an image is not tagged, Docker defaults to using the 'latest' version of the image. However, the 'latest' tag does not guarantee that the same version of an image will be used every time, which can lead to unexpected behavior or compatibility issues.\n\nTo comply with this rule, always specify a version number when pulling a Docker image. Instead of `FROM debian`, write `FROM debian:unstable` or `FROM debian:10.3`. This ensures that you are using a specific version of the image, providing a more predictable and stable environment for your project."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/tag-image-version","id":"docker-best-practices/tag-image-version","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Always tag the version of an image"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"The rule \"Always use -y with apt-get install\" is a best practice in Dockerfile development to ensure that the Docker build process is non-interactive. Dockerfiles should be designed to build without requiring any user intervention. By using the `-y` flag with `apt-get install`, you can automatically answer yes to any prompts that the installation process might produce, making the process non-interactive.\n\nThis rule is crucial because a Docker build that requires user interaction can cause problems in automated build systems. It can lead to build failures or unexpected results due to lack of user response. This is especially important in CI/CD pipelines where the Docker build process should be fully automated.\n\nTo adhere to this rule, always include the `-y` flag when using `apt-get install` in your Dockerfiles. For example, instead of writing `RUN apt-get install gcc`, write `RUN apt-get install -y gcc`. Also, to avoid potential issues with locale settings, you can use `DEBIAN_FRONTEND=noninteractive` in conjunction with `apt-get install`. For instance, `RUN DEBIAN_FRONTEND=noninteractive apt-get update && apt-get install -y git`."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/apt-get-yes","id":"docker-best-practices/apt-get-yes","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Always use -y with apt-get install"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"When using `yum` to install a package, make sure you use the `-y` flag to avoid your CI being blocked on a prompt."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/yum-use-y","id":"docker-best-practices/yum-use-y","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Always use -y with yum install"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"Do not use `root` as the last user because your container runs with the `root` user. Always use a user with lower privileges."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/no-root-user","id":"docker-best-practices/no-root-user","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS","CWE:250"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Last user should not be root"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"Use `LABEL` instead of `MAINTAINER` to report the maintainer of a Dockerfile."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/maintainer-deprecated","id":"docker-best-practices/maintainer-deprecated","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"The maintainer entry is deprecated"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"A Dockerfile with multiple `HEALTHCHECK` instructions is confusing. A container should only have one `HEALTHCHECK` instruction."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/multiple-healthcheck","id":"docker-best-practices/multiple-healthcheck","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Do not use multiple HEALTHCHECK"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"This rule emphasizes the importance of pinning versions when using pip to install Python packages in your Dockerfile. Pinning versions means specifying the exact version of the package you want to install. Without pinning, pip installs the latest version of the package, which may not be compatible with your application.\n\nPinning versions is crucial for maintaining the stability and reproducibility of your Docker images. Without pinning, your builds could suddenly start failing because of a new package version that introduces breaking changes. Your application could also behave differently or even fail when running in different environments, due to variations in package versions.\n\nTo avoid these issues, always specify the exact version of the package when using pip install. For example, instead of `RUN pip install django`, use `RUN pip install django==1.9`. If you have a list of packages to install, you can put them in a requirements.txt file with their versions pinned, and then install them with `RUN pip install -r requirements.txt`. This practice will ensure that you always know exactly what versions of packages are in your Docker images, and your builds will be stable and reproducible."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/pip-pin-versions","id":"docker-best-practices/pip-pin-versions","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Always pin versions with pip"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"The `EXPOSE` instruction should take a valid UNIX port range."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/expose-valid-port","id":"docker-best-practices/expose-valid-port","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Expose a valid UNIX port number"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"When using multiple images in a Dockerfile, aliases must be unique."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/alias-must-be-unique","id":"docker-best-practices/alias-must-be-unique","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"FROM aliases must be unique"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"The Dockerfile CMD instruction provides defaults for an executing container. These can include an executable, or they can omit the executable, in which case you must specify an ENTRYPOINT instruction. However, if you use multiple CMD instructions in a Dockerfile, only the last CMD instruction takes effect.\n\nUsing multiple CMD instructions in a Dockerfile can lead to confusion and unexpected behavior when the Docker image is run (only the last CMD instruction is executed). This can potentially lead to parts of your application not running as expected or not running at all.\n\nTo avoid this, ensure that you only use one CMD instruction in your Dockerfile. If you have multiple commands that need to be run, consider using a script to encapsulate these commands and then call this script in your CMD instruction. For example, instead of having `CMD run_server1` and `CMD run_server2`, you could have a script called `run_servers.sh` that contains the commands `run_server1` and `run_server2`, and then your Dockerfile would contain `CMD ./run_servers.sh`. This way, all your commands are run as expected."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/multiple-cmd","id":"docker-best-practices/multiple-cmd","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Do not use multiple CMD"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"Do not use multiple `ENTRYPOINT` instructions, only the last one is used."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/multiple-entrypoint","id":"docker-best-practices/multiple-entrypoint","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Do not use multiple ENTRYPOINT"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"Never expose admin ports such as the SSH port `22` in your container. It increases the surface of attack of your containers."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/expose-admin-ports","id":"docker-best-practices/expose-admin-ports","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS","CWE:284"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Do not expose sensitive ports"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"Make sure you do not give too many permissions with copying or adding a file. Adding write permissions to all means that any other users may modify the files.\n"},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/avoid-chmod-777","id":"docker-best-practices/avoid-chmod-777","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS","CWE:732"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Do not give wide permissions on files"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"This rule states that Dockerfiles should not use a cache when installing packages. When building Docker images, Docker has a built-in caching mechanism that reuses instructions from previous builds, which can speed up the build process. However, when installing packages, this can lead to outdated packages being used, which might have security vulnerabilities or bugs.\n\nIt is important to avoid using a cache when installing packages because it ensures that the latest version of a package is always used. This reduces the risk of security vulnerabilities and bugs, and ensures that your application has the most up-to-date and secure dependencies.\n\nWhen installing packages with pip in a Dockerfile, use the `--no-cache-dir` option. This tells pip not to use a cache when installing packages, which ensures that the latest version of the package is always used. For example, instead of writing `RUN pip install django`, write `RUN pip install --no-cache-dir django`."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/pip-no-cache","id":"docker-best-practices/pip-no-cache","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Do not use cache when installing packages"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"When using `dnf` to install a package, make sure you use the `-y` flag to avoid your CI being blocked on a prompt."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/dnf-use-y","id":"docker-best-practices/dnf-use-y","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Always use -y with dnf install"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"When using `zypper` to install a package, make sure you use the `-y` flag to avoid your CI being blocked on a prompt.\n"},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/zypper-use-y","id":"docker-best-practices/zypper-use-y","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Always use -y with zypper install"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"Always use `https` links instead of `http`. Do not use clear-text protocols as they lack encryption and authentication."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/avoid-http","id":"docker-best-practices/avoid-http","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS","CWE:319"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Avoid fetching data from HTTP endpoint"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"The rule stipulates that all Dockerfiles must specify a base image. This is important because without specifying a base image, you are building a container from scratch, and this is likely what is not intended.\n\nTo avoid violating this rule, always declare a base image at the start of your Dockerfile using the `FROM` keyword. For example, `FROM ubuntu:18.04` sets the base image to Ubuntu 18.04."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/no-from-image","id":"docker-best-practices/no-from-image","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Dockerfiles should specify a base image"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"This rule aims to prevent privilege escalation vulnerabilities in Docker Compose configurations by ensuring that the `no-new-privileges` security option is enabled. Privilege escalation occurs when a container can gain additional rights beyond its intended permissions, potentially compromising the host system or other containers.\n\nEnabling `no-new-privileges:true` in the `security_opt` section of a service ensures that processes inside the container cannot gain new privileges via setuid or setgid binaries. This restriction helps maintain a secure environment by limiting the container's ability to perform unauthorized actions, reducing the attack surface.\n\n\nTo comply with this rule, ensure that your Docker images use the `no-new-privileges` directive like below.\n\n```yaml\nsecurity_opt:\n  - no-new-privileges:true\n```"},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/no-new-privileges","id":"docker-best-practices/no-new-privileges","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS","CWE:732"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Avoid privilege escalation via setuid or setgid"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"This rule advises against configuring services with a writable filesystem in Docker Compose files. Allowing a writable filesystem can increase the attack surface by enabling potential attackers or malicious processes to modify the container’s file system, which could lead to unauthorized changes or persistence of malicious code.\n\nEnsuring that services run with a read-only filesystem enhances security by preventing in-container modifications during runtime. This practice helps maintain the integrity of the container environment and reduces the risk of accidental or intentional file tampering.\n\nTo comply with this rule, explicitly set `read_only: true` for your service definitions in the Docker Compose YAML file. For example, use `read_only: true` under the service configuration to enforce a read-only root filesystem.\n\nBy adopting this approach, you improve the overall security posture of your containerized applications and make them more resilient against attacks or unintended changes."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/service-writable-filesystem","id":"docker-best-practices/service-writable-filesystem","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS","CWE:732"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Avoid service with writable filesystem"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"This rule enforces the use of the `--no-install-recommends` option when installing packages with `apt-get` in Dockerfiles. The `--no-install-recommends` flag ensures that only essential packages are installed, avoiding unnecessary recommended packages that can bloat the image size.\n\nTo comply with this rule, always include `--no-install-recommends` in your `apt-get install` commands, for example: `apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends gcc`."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/apt-get-no-install-recommends","id":"docker-best-practices/apt-get-no-install-recommends","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Do not use no-install-recommends"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"This rule encourages the use of `COPY` instead of `ADD` in Dockerfiles when simply copying files or directories. While both instructions can copy files into the image, `ADD` has additional functionality such as extracting local tar archives and fetching remote URLs.\n\nTo make your Dockerfiles more uniform and predictable, you should use `COPY` unless you need `ADD`'s extra functionality.\n\nSee [official Docker documentation](https://docs.docker.com/build/building/best-practices/#add-or-copy)"},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/avoid-add-use-copy","id":"docker-best-practices/avoid-add-use-copy","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Use COPY instead of ADD"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"This rule encourages the use of the `SHELL` instruction to explicitly change the default shell in a Dockerfile rather than modifying it indirectly through commands like `RUN ln -sfv /bin/bash /bin/sh`. Using `SHELL` provides a clear and declarative way to specify which shell should be used for subsequent instructions, improving readability and maintainability.\n\nTo comply with this rule, replace any commands that attempt to change the default shell indirectly, such as `RUN ln -sfv /bin/bash /bin/sh`, with the `SHELL` instruction like `SHELL [\"/bin/bash\", \"-c\"]`. This approach keeps your Dockerfile clean and ensures consistent execution of shell commands."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/change-default-shell","id":"docker-best-practices/change-default-shell","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Use SHELL to change the default shell"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"This rule enforces that when the COPY instruction in a Dockerfile has more than two arguments, the last argument must be a directory path ending with a slash (/). This ensures that multiple source files or directories are copied into the specified destination directory correctly. Always ensure that when copying multiple files or directories, the destination path ends with a slash, clearly indicating it is a directory. For example, use `COPY package.json yarn.lock my_app/` instead of `COPY package.json yarn.lock my_app`. This practice improves clarity and prevents ambiguous or incorrect Docker image builds."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/copy-end-slash","id":"docker-best-practices/copy-end-slash","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"COPY with more than 2 args must end with /"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"This rule enforces that the `COPY` instruction must reference a valid build stage alias defined by a preceding `FROM` statement using the `as` keyword. Specifically, the `--from` flag in `COPY` should only point to an existing build stage alias, ensuring that the source files are correctly retrieved from the intended build context.\n\nTo avoid violations, always declare build stages with `FROM <image> as <alias>` before using `COPY --from=<alias>`. Verify that the alias used in `COPY` matches exactly with the alias declared in the earlier `FROM` statement. For example, using `FROM debian:jesse as build` followed by `COPY --from=build ...` ensures compliance and reliable builds."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/copy-reference-from","id":"docker-best-practices/copy-reference-from","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"COPY cannot reference the FROM alias"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"This rule enforces the use of either `wget` or `curl` exclusively within a Dockerfile, but not both. Mixing these two tools in the same Dockerfile can lead to unnecessary complexity and larger image sizes due to installing multiple similar utilities. It also reduces consistency and maintainability of the Dockerfile.\n\nTo comply with this rule, choose either `wget` or `curl` based on your preference or the base image's default availability, and use it consistently throughout your Dockerfile. For example, if you decide to use `curl`, replace all occurrences of `wget` with equivalent `curl` commands like `curl -O <url>`. This approach ensures clarity and reduces the image footprint."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/curl-or-wget","id":"docker-best-practices/curl-or-wget","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Use either wget or curl but not both"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"This rule advises against referencing an environment variable within the same `ENV` instruction in a Dockerfile. For example, writing `ENV FOO=bar \\ BAZ=$FOO/bla` is problematic because the Docker build process does not expand environment variables declared in the same `ENV` command.\n\nTo avoid this issue, declare each environment variable in a separate `ENV` instruction if you need to reference a previously set variable. For instance, use `ENV FOO=bar` followed by `ENV BAZ=${FOO}/bla`. This ensures that `FOO` is properly set and expanded when `BAZ` is defined, leading to more reliable and predictable builds."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/env-no-refer-envvar","id":"docker-best-practices/env-no-refer-envvar","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Do not refer to an environment variable within the same ENV"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"This rule enforces that the very first instruction in a Dockerfile must be either `ARG` or `FROM`. These instructions are fundamental for defining the build-time variables and the base image, respectively, which are crucial for the Docker build process to function correctly. Starting with `ARG` or `FROM` ensures that the build context is properly initialized before any other commands are executed. This helps avoid unexpected behaviors or errors during the build, as Docker needs a base image or build argument context to interpret subsequent instructions."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/first-instruction","id":"docker-best-practices/first-instruction","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"First instruction should be ARG or FROM"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"Using the `latest` tag can lead to unpredictable builds because the base image may be updated without notice, potentially introducing breaking changes or vulnerabilities. This unpredictability makes it difficult to reproduce builds reliably or troubleshoot issues that arise due to unexpected image updates.\n\nTo comply with this rule, specify an explicit version or tag for the base image, such as `debian:jessie` or `python:3.9-slim`. Pinning the base image to a specific version ensures consistent and repeatable builds, improving stability and security by preventing unintended updates."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/no-latest-tag","id":"docker-best-practices/no-latest-tag","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS","CWE:829"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Do not use latest tag"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":""},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/onbuild-allowed-actions","id":"docker-best-practices/onbuild-allowed-actions","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"FROM or MAINTAINER cannot be triggered within ONBUILD"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"This rule enforces the use of only allowed registries in the `FROM` instruction of a Dockerfile. It ensures that base images are pulled from trusted and verified sources, reducing the risk of introducing malicious or unverified software into your container environment.\n\nTo comply with this rule, always specify base images using registries that are explicitly permitted by your organization's policies. For example, use `FROM python:3.6` or `FROM docker.io/python:3.6` instead of `FROM randomrepo/python:3.6`. This practice helps ensure that the images you use are reliable and vetted.\n\nYou can specify the exact list of registries to check by defining the `registries` argument and separate them with a comma. There is an example of how to tweak your configuration file to add `registry1` and `registry2`.\n\n```yaml\nrulesets:\n  - docker-best-practices:\n    rules:\n      only-use-allowed-registry:\n        arguments:\n          registries: registry1,registry2\n```"},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/only-use-allowed-registry","id":"docker-best-practices/only-use-allowed-registry","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Use only an allowed registry in the FROM image"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"This rule encourages the use of absolute paths or the `WORKDIR` instruction to change directories within Dockerfiles instead of chaining commands with `cd`. Using relative paths combined with `cd` in a single `RUN` instruction can lead to less readable and more error-prone code. It also makes it harder to track the current working directory during image builds.\n\nTo comply, either set the working directory explicitly using `WORKDIR /path/to/directory` before running commands or use absolute paths in instructions like `RUN cp /source/file /destination/path`. Avoid combining `cd` with other commands in a single `RUN` line, as this can cause unexpected behavior and complicate debugging."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/use-absolute-paths","id":"docker-best-practices/use-absolute-paths","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Use absolute paths or. use WORKDIR to switch directories"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"When building Docker images, using `useradd -l` ensures that the new user is created without adding entries to system login tracking files like `/var/log/lastlog` or `/var/log/faillog`. These files are irrelevant in containers since they don’t persist user sessions or keep login histories, and in minimal images they may not even exist, which can lead to errors or unnecessary file creation during build.\n\nThis makes your image smaller, cleaner, and more reliable. Since containers are designed to run processes rather than serve as full login environments, disabling login record tracking speeds up builds, avoids warnings, and follows best practices for lightweight, secure Docker images."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/useradd-l-flag","id":"docker-best-practices/useradd-l-flag","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Use -l with useradd"}},{"fullDescription":{"text":"This rule ensures that after running `yarn install` in a Dockerfile, a `yarn cache clean` command is executed to remove unnecessary cache files. This practice helps to minimize the image size by cleaning up temporary files and caches that are not needed for the runtime environment.\nmes.\n\nTo comply with this rule, always chain `yarn install` with `yarn cache clean` in the same RUN instruction like `RUN yarn install && yarn cache clean`. This approach ensures that the cache cleanup happens immediately after installation, reducing the number of layers and keeping the image optimized."},"helpUri":"https://docs.datadoghq.com/static_analysis/rules/docker-best-practices/yarn-clean","id":"docker-best-practices/yarn-clean","properties":{"tags":["DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:STATIC_ANALYSIS"]},"shortDescription":{"text":"Run yarn clean after yarn install"}}],"version":"0.8.4"}}}],"version":"2.1.0"}